WHO   — Ptahhotep — vizier to Pharaoh Djedkare Isesi and named author of the Maxims of Ptahhotep — the Instruction: a father's counsel on justice, restraint, truth (ma'at), and right conduct
WHAT  — vizier to Pharaoh Djedkare Isesi and named author of the Maxims of Ptahhotep — the Instruction: a father's counsel on justice, restraint, truth (ma'at), and right conduct
WHERE — AMP · The Greek Mirror — Memphis · Egypt (Old Kingdom, 5th Dynasty)  Framework inputs: the world's philosophers by year and location; the mirror that looks past Greece  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — He is the first man seated by the elder date: ethics set down as teaching. Honest seam — the Maxims survive only in much later copies (the Papyrus Prisse, Middle Kingdom), so the man is older than any page we hold of him, and 'philosopher' here means sage of wisdom-literature.
HOW   — Seated in the Amphitheater of the World's Philosophers, by year and location.

